RTS Futures Gain as Oil Advances, U.S. Jobs Data Fuels Optimism

-- B y   H a l i a   P a v l i v a
-- 
2011-07-07T21:24:22Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-07/rts-futures-gain-as-oil-advances-u-s-jobs-data-fuels-optimism.html
Russia ’s RTS stock-index futures
gained as U.S. jobs and retail-sales data bolstered optimism
about the economy and oil, the country’s major export earner,
climbed to a three-week high.  Futures on the dollar-denominated index expiring in
September gained 0.2 percent yesterday, rising for an eighth day
in nine. Contracts on OAO Rosneft, the country’s biggest oil
producer, gained 0.4 percent and agreements on OAO Lukoil, the
second-largest, climbed 0.3 percent. Futures on OAO Gazprom, the
world’s largest gas producer, rose 0.2 percent.  “The news flow has been positive today and that has formed
optimistic expectations among investors,” Elena Matrosova, a
Moscow-based economist at BDO International, a financial adviser
that lists the central bank among its clients, said in a
telephone interview yesterday. “ Oil prices  also helped.”  Crude oil for August delivery increased 2.1 percent to
$98.67 a barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange , the highest
settlement since June 14. Prices have climbed 33 percent in the
past year. Oil and gas account for about 17 percent of Russia’s
gross domestic product.  Russia, the world’s largest energy exporter, also exports
natural gas and metals, including gold, steel, nickel, copper.
The Thomson Reuters/Jefferies CRB Index of 19 raw materials rose
1.8 percent yesterday, the most since May 18.  The Standard & Poor’s 500 Index gained 1.1 percent to
1,353.22 at 4 p.m. in  New York , its highest close since May 10.
The MSCI Emerging Markets Index advanced 0.6 percent.  U.S. Data  Companies in the U.S. added twice as many workers as
forecast in June, signaling an improvement in the labor market.
The 157,000 increase followed a 36,000 gain the prior month,
according to data from ADP Employer Services. Jobless claims
fell by 14,000 to 418,000 in the week ended July 2, Labor
Department figures showed. U.S. same store sales excluding Wal-
Mart rose 6.9 percent in June from a year earlier, according to
the  International Council of Shopping Centers .  The Market Vectors Russia ETF, a U.S.-traded fund that
holds Russian shares, added 2.2 percent yesterday. The American
depositary receipts of Lukoil advanced 2.1 percent yesterday,
while ADRs of Gazprom rose 3.8 percent.  Russia’s 30-stock, ruble-denominated  Micex index (INDEXCF)  rallied
the most in two months, gaining 2.1 percent to 1,740.53
yesterday. The dollar-denominated RTS Index increased 2 percent
to 1,976.9 yesterday.  To contact the reporter on this story:
